<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>
<section xml:id="sec-CompProp" xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude">
  <title>z-test for Two Proportions</title>

  <introduction>
  <p> In this section we will test the equality of two proportions. </p>
  <p> A two-proportion <m>z</m>-test is used to determine whether two population
  proportions are significantly different. It compares the difference between two
  sample proportions to what would be expected by random chance if the population
  proportions were actually equal. This test is commonly used when data are
  collected from two independent groups and the response for each individual
  falls into one of two categories, such as success or failure.
  </p>
  </introduction>

  <objectives>
  <introduction>
    <p> At the end of this section you will be able to:   </p>
  </introduction>
  <ol>
    <li> <p> Write hypotheses for the difference in proportions. </p> </li>
    <li> <p> Determine the test statistic and p-value for the z-test for two proportions. </p> </li>
     <li> <p> Write the conclusion of a test in context </p> </li>
     <li> <p> Construct confidence intervals for the difference in proportions. </p> </li>
        </ol>
</objectives>


<subsection xml:id="subsec-CompareProportionsBasics">
  <title>Understanding the Basics</title>
 <p> The two-proportion <m>z</m>-test is used to compare the proportions of a particular outcome in two populations and determine whether there is evidence of a difference between them. This test is appropriate when each individual in both samples is classified into one of two categories, such as success or failure, yes or no, or support or do not support. The <term> hypotheses</term> are written in terms of the population proportions <m>p_1</m> and <m>p_2</m>. The null hypothesis is often written as </p> 
 <p><m>p_1-p_2=0</m> or  <m>p_1 = p_2</m>. </p> 
 <p> The alternative hypothesis is writing as either <m>p_1 \lt p_2</m> or <m>p_1 \gt p_2</m> for a one tailed test, or <m>p_1 \ne p_2</m> for a two tailed test. </p>
<p>The <term>test statistic</term> is
<md> z=\frac{(\hat{p}_1-\hat{p}_2)-0}{\sqrt{\bar{p}\left(1-\bar{p}\right)\left(\frac{1}{n_1}+\frac{1}{n_2}\right)}} </md>
where <m>\hat{p}_1=\dfrac{x_1}{n_1}</m> and <m>\hat{p}_2=\dfrac{x_2}{n_2}</m> are the sample proportions, and <m> \bar{p}=\frac{x_1+x_2}{n_1+n_2} </m>
is the pooled estimate for the population proportion. </p>
<p> This test assumes that the two samples are independently selected, that the observations within each sample are independent, and that the sampling distribution of the difference in sample proportions is approximately normal. The normality condition is satisfied when there are at least 10 successes and 10 failures in each group. The samples should be random samples.</p>
<p>The resulting <term>p-value</term> is used to determine whether the observed difference between sample proportions provides enough evidence to conclude that the two population proportions differ.</p>
<p> Recall that when the <em>p-value</em> <m>  \lt \alpha </m> we reject the null hypothesis, otherwise there is not enough evidence to reject the null hypothesis. </p>

<definition xml:id="def-two-proportion-z-test">
  <statement>
    <p>
      A <term>two-proportion <m>z</m>-test</term> is a statistical test used to
      compare two population proportions and determine whether there is evidence
      of a difference between them.
    </p>
    <p>
      The test statistic is
        <md>
z=\frac{(\hat{p}_1-\hat{p}_2)-0}{\sqrt{\bar{p}(1-\bar{p})\left(\frac{1}{n_1}+\frac{1}{n_2}\right)}}
    </md> </p>
    <p>
      where <m>\hat{p}_1=\dfrac{x_1}{n_1}</m> and <m>\hat{p}_2=\dfrac{x_2}{n_2}</m>
      are the sample proportions, and
      <m>\bar{p}=\dfrac{x_1+x_2}{n_1+n_2}</m> is the pooled sample proportion.
    </p>
  </statement>
</definition>

 <p> At times, we may want to find the confidence interval for the difference in proportions. It is important to pay attention to which variable is listed first since this can change the interpretation. </p> 
 <definition xml:id="def-ci-difference-proportions">
  <statement>
    <p>
      A <term>confidence interval for the difference in proportions</term> is an
      interval estimate used to estimate the difference between two population
      proportions, <m>p_1-p_2</m>, based on two independent random samples.
    </p>
    <p>
      A confidence interval for <m>p_1-p_2</m> is given by
        <md>
(\hat{p}_1-\hat{p}_2)\pm z^\ast \sqrt{\frac{\hat{p}_1(1-\hat{p}_1)}{n_1}+\frac{\hat{p}_2(1-\hat{p}_2)}{n_2}}
    </md> </p>
    <p>
      where <m>\hat{p}_1</m> and <m>\hat{p}_2</m> are the sample proportions,
      <m>n_1</m> and <m>n_2</m> are the sample sizes, and <m>z^\ast</m> is the
      critical value from the standard normal distribution corresponding to the
      desired confidence level.
    </p>
  </statement>
</definition>


</subsection> 

<subsection xml:id="subsec-CompareProportionsDrivers">
  <title>Compare Proportions Without Insurance</title>
<p>
      Transportation researchers want to determine whether the proportion of
      drivers without auto insurance differs between California and Colorado.
      Suppose a random sample of <m>800</m> drivers is selected from California,
      and <m>163</m> of them are found to be driving without auto insurance. A
      separate random sample of <m>750</m> drivers is selected from Colorado,
      and <m>146</m> of them are found to be driving without auto insurance.
    </p>
    <p>
      These sample results correspond to sample proportions of approximately
      <m>20.41\%</m> for California and <m>19.47\%</m> for Colorado.
    </p>
    <p>
      At the <m>\alpha =0.10</m> significance level, test whether the population
      proportion of drivers without auto insurance differs between the two
      states.
    </p>
<example> <title> Uninsured Drivers by State</title> 
  <statement>
<p>
      State the null and alternative hypotheses, verify the conditions for a
      two-sample <m>z</m>-test for proportions, compute the pooled estimate and the test statistic,  find the p-value, and state your conclusion in context.
    </p>
  </statement>
  <solution><title> Hypotheses</title>
    <p>
      Let <m>p_1</m> be the population proportion of drivers without auto
      insurance in California, and let <m>p_2</m> be the population proportion
      in Colorado.
    </p>
    <p> The null and alternative hypotheses for there is no difference between the proportions or there is a difference in proportions are:  
            <md> H_0:p_1-p_2=0 \qquad H_a:p_1-p_2\ne 0.  </md></p>
        <p> The null hypothesis is that the two proportions are equal and the alternative hypothesis is that the proportions are not equal to each other. 
          <md> H_0:p_1 =p_2 \qquad H_a:p_1 \ne p_2.  </md>
This is a two tailed test. </p> 
</solution> 
<solution> <title> Sample Statistics</title>
    <p>
      The sample sizes and sample proportions are
        <md>
n_1=800,\quad x_1=163,\quad \hat{p}_1=\frac{163}{800}=0.20375
    </md>
    <md>
n_2=750,\quad x_2=146,\quad \hat{p}_2=\frac{146}{750}\approx 0.19467.
    </md></p>
         <p>The pooled sample proportion is
    <md> \bar{p}=\frac{x_1+x_2}{n_1+n_2}
=\frac{163+146}{800+750} =\frac{309}{1550} \approx 0.19935.     </md>
</p>
</solution> 
<solution> <title> Assumptions</title>
    <p> We check the success-failure conditions that <m>np \ge 10</m> and <m>n(1-p) \ge 10</m> for both samples:
        <md>
n_1\hat{p}=800(0.19935)\approx 159.48,\qquad
n_1(1-\hat{p})=800(0.80065)\approx 640.52
    </md>
    <md>
n_2\hat{p}=750(0.19935)\approx 149.52,\qquad
n_2(1-\hat{p})=750(0.80065)\approx 600.48.
    </md></p>
    <p>
      All four values are greater than <m>10</m>, so the normal approximation
      is appropriate for the z-test for proportions.
    </p>
</solution> 
<solution> <title> Statistical Test</title>
    <p> The test statistic is
        <md> z=\frac{(\hat{p}_1-\hat{p}_2)-0}
{\sqrt{\bar{p}(1-\bar{p})\left(\frac{1}{n_1}+\frac{1}{n_2}\right)}}
=\frac{0.20375-0.19467}
{\sqrt{(0.19935)(0.80065)\left(\frac{1}{800}+\frac{1}{750}\right)}}
\approx \frac{0.00908}{0.02029}
\approx 0.45.     </md> </p>
</solution>
<solution> <title> p-value</title>
    <p>
      The p-value for a two-tailed test is
        <m> 2 P(Z \gt 0.45)\approx 2(0.326) \approx 0.652. </m></p>
    <p>
      Since the <term>p-value</term> is greater than <m>0.10</m>, we fail to
      reject <m>H_0</m>.
    </p>
</solution> 
<solution> <title> Conclusion</title>
    <p>
      At the <m>\alpha =0.10</m> significance level, there is not sufficient evidence to conclude that the population proportions of drivers without auto
      insurance differ between California and Colorado.
    </p>
  </solution>
</example> 


    <p>
      Construct a <m>90\%</m> confidence interval for the difference
      <m>p_1-p_2</m>, where <m>p_1</m> is the population proportion for
      California and <m>p_2</m> is the population proportion for Colorado.
    </p>
<example> <title> Interval for Difference in Uninsured </title>
  <statement>
  <p>
      Construct a <m>90\%</m> confidence interval for the difference
      <m>p_1-p_2</m>, where <m>p_1</m> is the population proportion for
      California and <m>p_2</m> is the population proportion for Colorado.
    </p>
  </statement>
  <solution> <title> Sample Statistics</title>
    <p>
      First compute the sample proportions:
        <md> \hat{p}_1=\frac{163}{800}=0.20375
    </md>
    <md> \hat{p}_2=\frac{146}{750}\approx 0.19467
    </md> </p>
    <p>
      The point estimate for the difference in proportions is
        <md> \hat{p}_1-\hat{p}_2=0.20375-0.19467=0.00908
    </md></p>
</solution>
<solution> <title> Interval</title>
    <p>
      For a <m>95\%</m> confidence interval, the critical value is
      <m>z^\ast=1.96</m>.
    </p>
    <p>
      The standard error is
        <md>
SE=\sqrt{\frac{\hat{p}_1(1-\hat{p}_1)}{n_1}+\frac{\hat{p}_2(1-\hat{p}_2)}{n_2}}
=\sqrt{\frac{(0.20375)(0.79625)}{800}+\frac{(0.19467)(0.80533)}{750}}
    </md>
    <md>
SE=\sqrt{\frac{0.1622265625}{800}+\frac{0.1567795111}{750}}
=\sqrt{0.0002028+0.0002090}
=\sqrt{0.0004118}
\approx 0.02029
    </md> </p>
    <p>
      The margin of error is
        <md> ME=z^\ast \cdot SE=1.645(0.02029)\approx 0.03338
    </md> </p>
    <p>
      Therefore, the <m>95\%</m> confidence interval is
    <md> (\bar{p}_1-\bar{p}_2)\pm ME
=0.00908\pm 0.03338
    </md>
    <md>
(-0.0243,\ 0.04246)
    </md> </p>
    <p>
      We are <m>90\%</m> confident that the difference in the population
      proportions of drivers without auto insurance in California and Colorado
      is between -2.4% and 4.2%. Since this interval
      contains <m>0</m>, the data do not suggest a clear difference between the
      two state proportions.
    </p>
  </solution>
</example>

  </subsection>

<subsection xml:id="subsec-CompareProportionsMimicry">
  <title>Compare Proportions of Mimicry Repertoires </title>
  <p>Parrots are one of the rare animal taxa with life-long vocal learning. Parrot vocal repertoires are difficult to study in the wild, but companion parrots offer a valuable data source. Researchers surveyed the public about mimicry repertoires in companion parrots. </p>
    <p> Researchers were curious whether the proportion of parrots with large mimicry repertoires differs between males and females. We will define a <q>success</q> as a parrot having a mimicry repertoire of more than <m>20</m> mimicked sounds, words, or phrases. </p>
    <p>
      Suppose that in a sample of <m>180</m> male parrots, <m>54</m> had
      repertoires larger than <m>20</m>, while in a sample of <m>160</m> female
      parrots, <m>32</m> had repertoires larger than <m>20</m> mimicked sounds.
    </p>
    <p>
      At the <m>\alpha = 0.05</m> significance level, test whether the population
      proportions differ for male and female parrots.
    </p>
<example> <title> Parrot Mimicry by Sex </title>
  <statement>
<p>
      State the null and alternative hypotheses, verify the conditions for a
      two-sample <m>z</m>-test for proportions, compute the pooled estimate and the test statistic,  find the p-value, and state your conclusion in context.
    </p>
  </statement>
  <solution><title> Hypotheses </title>
    <p>
      Let <m>p_1</m> be the population proportion of male parrots with mimicry
      repertoires greater than 20 sounds, and let <m>p_2</m> be the population
      proportion of female parrots with mimicry repertoires greater than
      20 sounds.
    </p>
    <p>
      The null hypothesis is that the proportions are equal while the alternative hypothesis is that the proportions are not equal. 
        <md> H_0:p_1-= p_2  \qquad H_a:p_1 \ne p_2    </md>
This is a two tailed test. </p>
</solution>
<solution><title> Sample Statistics </title>
<p> The sample proportions are
        <md>  x_1=54,\quad n_1=180,\quad \hat{p}_1=\frac{54}{180}=0.30     </md>
    <md> x_2=32,\quad n_2=160,\quad \hat{p}_2=\frac{32}{160}=0.20.     </md> </p>
    <p>  The pooled sample proportion is
    <md> \bar{p}=\frac{x_1+x_2}{n_1+n_2}
=\frac{54+32}{180+160} =\frac{86}{340} \approx 0.2529.     </md> </p>
</solution> 
<solution><title> Assumptions </title>
    <p>  We check the success-failure conditions:
        <md>
n_1\hat{p}=180(0.2529)\approx 45.52,\qquad
n_1(1-\hat{p})=180(0.7471)\approx 134.48
    </md>
    <md>
n_2\hat{p}=160(0.2529)\approx 40.46,\qquad
n_2(1-\hat{p})=160(0.7471)\approx 119.54.
    </md>
</p> 
    <p>
      All four values are greater than 10, so the normal approximation
      is appropriate for the difference in proportions test.
    </p>
</solution>
<solution><title> Statistical Test </title>
    <p> The test statistic is
        <md> z=\frac{(\hat{p}_1-\hat{p}_2)-0}
{\sqrt{\bar{p}(1-\bar{p})\left(\frac{1}{n_1}+\frac{1}{n_2}\right)}}
=\frac{0.30-0.20}
{\sqrt{(0.2529)(0.7471)\left(\frac{1}{180}+\frac{1}{160}\right)}}
\approx \frac{0.10}{0.0469} \approx 2.13.     </md> </p>
</solution>
<solution><title> p-value</title>
    <p>  The p-value  for a two-tailed test is <m>\approx 2(0.017) \approx0.034  </m></p>
    <p>  Since the p-value is less than <m>\alpha =0.05</m>, we reject
      <m>H_0</m>.  </p>
</solution>
<solution><title> Conclusion </title>
    <p>
      At the <m>\alpha = 0.05</m> significance level, there is sufficient evidence to
      conclude that the proportions of male parrots with mimicry repertoires greater than 20 sounds differs from the proportion of female parrots with
      mimicry repertoires greater than 20 sounds differ.
    </p>
  </solution>
</example>

<p>
      Construct a <m>95\%</m> confidence interval for the difference in proportions, 
      <m>p_1-p_2</m>, where <m>p_1</m> is the population proportion for male
      parrots and <m>p_2</m> is the population proportion for female parrots.
    </p>

<example> <title>Interval for Difference in Mimicry</title>
<statement> 
<p>
      Construct a <m>95\%</m> confidence interval for the difference
      in proportions between male parrots and female parrots who had repertoires larger than 20  mimicked sounds.
    </p>
  </statement>
  <solution> <title> Sample Statistics</title>
    <p>  First compute the sample proportions:
    <md> \hat{p}_1=\frac{54}{180}=0.30
    </md>
    <md> \hat{p}_2=\frac{32}{160}=0.20
    </md>     </p>
    <p>
      The point estimate for the difference in proportions is
    <md> \hat{p}_1-\hat{p}_2=0.30-0.20=0.10
    </md> </p>
    <p>
      For a <m>95\%</m> confidence interval, the critical value is
      <m>z^\ast=1.96</m>.
    </p>
    <p>
      The standard error is
    <md>
SE=\sqrt{\frac{\hat{p}_1(1-\hat{p}_1)}{n_1}+\frac{\hat{p}_2(1-\hat{p}_2)}{n_2}}
=\sqrt{\frac{(0.30)(0.70)}{180}+\frac{(0.20)(0.80)}{160}}
    </md>
    <md>
SE=\sqrt{\frac{0.21}{180}+\frac{0.16}{160}}
=\sqrt{0.0011667+0.0010000}
=\sqrt{0.0021667}
\approx 0.04655
    </md> </p>
    <p>  The margin of error is
    <md> ME=z^\ast \cdot SE=1.96(0.04655)\approx 0.09124
    </md></p>
    <p>       Therefore, the <m>95\%</m> confidence interval is
        <md> (\hat{p}_1-\hat{p}_2)\pm E =0.10\pm 0.09124
    </md>
    <md> (0.00876,\ 0.19124)
    </md> </p> 
    <p>
      We are <m>95\%</m> confident that the difference in the population
      proportions of male and female parrots with large mimicry repertoires is
      between 0.9% and 19.1%. Since the entire interval is positive and does not contain 0, the data suggest that the population proportion is higher for
      male parrots than for female parrots.
    </p>
  </solution>
</example> 


  </subsection>

  

<subsection xml:id="subsec-CompareProportionsCalc">
  <title>Using Technology</title>
  <p>
    We can use technology to perform a two-proportion z-test. The following example uses the TI-83 Plus calculator, but other calculators and statistical software packages can also be used.
  </p>
  <p>  An ornithologist, which is an avian biologist, wants to know whether the proportion of birds that mimicked <term>human sounds</term> differs between parrots and parakeets. Suppose a random sample of <m>120</m> parrots were observed, and <m>54</m> of them mimicked human sounds. In a separate random sample of <m>100</m> parakeets, <m>32</m> were observed to mimic human sounds.
    </p>
    <p>
      At the <m>\alpha =0.05</m> significance level, test whether the population
      proportions of parrots and parakeets that mimic human sounds are
      different.
    </p>
<example>  <title> Parrots vs Parakeets Sounds</title>
  <statement>
     <p> State the null and alternative hypotheses, verify the conditions for a
      two-sample <m>z</m>-test for proportions, compute the pooled estimate and the test statistic,  find the p-value, and state your conclusion in context. </p> 
  </statement>
  <solution><title> Hypotheses </title>
    <p>
      Let <m>p_1</m> be the population proportion of parrots that mimic human
      sounds, and let <m>p_2</m> be the population proportion of parakeets that
      mimic human sounds.
    </p>
    <p>  The hypotheses are the proportions are equal or the proportions are not equal:
        <md> H_0:p_1 =p_2 \qquad H_a:p_1 \ne p_2    </md>
This will be a two-tailed test. </p>
</solution>
<solution><title> Assumptions </title>
    <p>
      We check the success-failure conditions:
        <md> n_1\hat{p}=120(0.3909)\approx 46.91,\qquad n_1(1-\hat{p})=120(0.6091)\approx 73.09     </md>
    <md> n_2\hat{p}=100(0.3909)\approx 39.09,\qquad n_2(1-\hat{p})=100(0.6091)\approx 60.91.     </md> </p>
    <p>
      All four values are greater than <m>10</m>, so the normal approximation
      is appropriate for the difference in proportions z-test.
    </p>
</solution> 
<solution><title> Statistical Test </title>
    <p>
      The sample information is
    <md> x_1=54,\quad n_1=120,\quad \hat{p}_1=\frac{54}{120}=0.45     </md>
    <md> x_2=32,\quad n_2=100,\quad \hat{p}_2=\frac{32}{100}=0.32.   </md> </p>
    <p> The pooled sample proportion is
        <md> \bar{p}=\frac{x_1+x_2}{n_1+n_2} =\frac{54+32}{120+100} =\frac{86}{220}
\approx 0.3909.     </md> </p>
    <p> The test statistic is
        <md> z=\frac{(\hat{p}_1-\hat{p}_2)-0}
{\sqrt{\bar{p}(1-\bar{p})\left(\frac{1}{n_1}+\frac{1}{n_2}\right)}}
=\frac{0.45-0.32}
{\sqrt{(0.3909)(0.6091)\left(\frac{1}{120}+\frac{1}{100}\right)}}
\approx \frac{0.13}{0.0660} \approx 1.97.     </md> </p>
</solution>
<solution><title> p-value </title>
    <p>       The <term>p-value</term> for a two-tailed test is <m>\approx 2 (0.024) = 0.048.     </m></p>
     <p>  Since the <term>p-value</term> is less than <m>0.05</m>, we reject
      <m>H_0</m>.
    </p>
</solution>
    <solution><title> Conclusion </title>
<p>
      At the <m>0.05</m> significance level, there is sufficient evidence to
      conclude that the population proportions of parrots and parakeets that
      mimic human sounds are different.
    </p>
  </solution>

</example> 

<example> <title> Test Using TI-83 Plus </title>
<statement>
<p> For the TI-83 Plus you need to enter the counts for each sample. The calculator will calculate the <m> \hat{p}</m> values for each sample, the pooled <m> \bar{p}</m> value, and the test statistic <m>z</m>. See the previous example for the formula setup. </p>
</statement>
<solution><title> Statistical Test with TI-83 Plus</title>
<p> Click on the <term>[STAT] </term> button and press the arrow twice to the right to highlight TESTS across the top and select option <term>6: 2-PropZtest</term> and press [ENTER] to select it. </p>
<figure xml:id="Calculator2Proportion1">
            <caption>Selecting 2 Proportion Z-Test on Calculator</caption>
            <image source="ParakeetProp1.png" width="90%">
                <shortdescription>Select option 6 then input values</shortdescription>
            </image>
          </figure>

<p> Input the values from the samples. 
        <md>  x_1=54,\quad n_1=120  </md>
    <md> x_2=32,\quad n_2=100 </md> </p>
<p> Identify the alternative hypothesis of <m> \ne p2</m> and then click on <term>Calculate</term> and press [ENTER] to evaluate the test. </p> 
<figure xml:id="Calculator2Proportion2">
            <caption>Results 2 Proportion Z-Test between Parrots and Parakeets</caption>
            <image source="ParakeetProp2.png" width="90%">
                <shortdescription>z-test value is 1.9676 and p-value = 0.049</shortdescription>
            </image>
        </figure>

<p> The display gives the alternative hypothesis of not equal, the test statistic is <m>z=1.9676</m> with <m> p-value = 0.049</m>. Then it lists the sample proportions <m> p_1 = 0.45</m> and <m> p_2 = 0.32</m> and the pooled proportion <m> \bar{p} = 0.39 </m> </p> 
<p> If you select <term>Draw</term> it will graph the two-tailed test. </p>
<p> Since the p-value is less than 0.05, reject the null hypothesis. </p>
<p> there is sufficient evidence to conclude that the proportions of parrots and parakeets that mimic human sounds are different. </p> 

</solution> 
</example>

<example> <title> Confidence Interval with TI-83 Plus</title>
<statement>
<p> Find the 95% confidence interval for the difference in proportion between parrots and parakeets that mimic human sounds. </p>
</statement>
<solution> <title> Interval</title>
<p> Click on the <term>[STAT] </term> button and press the arrow twice to the right to highlight TESTS across the top and select option <term>B: 2-PropZInterval</term> on the TI83 Plus and press [ENTER] to select it. </p>
<figure xml:id="Calculator2Proportion3">
            <caption>Selecting 2 Proportion Interval </caption>
            <image source="ParakeetProp3.png" width="90%">
                <shortdescription>Select option B then input values</shortdescription>
            </image>
        </figure> 

<p> Input the values from the samples. 
        <md>  x_1=54,\quad n_1=120  </md>
    <md> x_2=32,\quad n_2=100 </md> </p>
<p> Change the C-lave to 0.95 then click on <term> Calculate</term> and press [ENTER] to evaluate the test. </p> 
<figure xml:id="Calculator2Proportion4">
            <caption>Interval Results for Difference in 2 Proportions between Parrots and Parakeets</caption>
            <image source="ParakeetProp4.png" width="50%">
                <shortdescription> interval .0024 to .2576</shortdescription>
            </image>
        </figure>

<p> The interval is <m> (0.0024 , 0.2576) </m> indicating we are 95% confident that the difference in proportions is between 0.24% and 25.76%, indicting that parrots mimic human sounds more. Since the interval does not contain <m>0</m> it is statistically significant. </p>
</solution>
</example>



  </subsection>

<subsection xml:id="subsec-CompareProportionsPractice">
  <title>Comparing Proportions Practice Problems</title>

 <exercise> <title> Marijuana </title>
  <statement>
    <p>
      A public health researcher wants to determine whether the proportion of
      college students who report using marijuana has changed over the past
      10 years. Ten years ago, a national survey found that <m>210</m>
      out of <m>1000</m> college students reported using marijuana. In a recent
      survey, <m>276</m> out of <m>1000</m> college students reported using
      marijuana.
    </p>
    <p>
      At the <m>\alpha =0.025</m> significance level, test whether the population
      proportion of college students who use marijuana today differs from the
      proportion from ten years ago.
    </p>
  </statement>
  <solution><title> Hypotheses</title>
    <p>
      Let <m>p_1</m> represent the population proportion of college students who
      used marijuana ten years ago, and let <m>p_2</m> represent the
      population proportion of college students who use marijuana today.
    </p>
    <p>
      The hypotheses are
        <md> H_0:p_1 =p_2  \qquad H_a:p_1 \ne p_2     </md>
This is a two-tailed test. </p>
</solution>
<solution> <title> Sample Statistics</title>
    <p> The sample information is
        <md>
x_1=210,\quad n_1=1000,\quad \hat{p}_1=\frac{210}{1000}=0.21
    </md>
    <md>
x_2=276,\quad n_2=1000,\quad \hat{p}_2=\frac{276}{1000}=0.276.
    </md> </p>
  <p>   The pooled sample proportion is
        <md> \bar{p}=\frac{x_1+x_2}{n_1+n_2}
=\frac{210+276}{1000+1000}
=\frac{486}{2000} =0.243.     </md> </p>
</solution>
<solution> <title> Assumptions</title>
    <p>       We check the success-failure conditions:
    <md>
n_1\hat{p}=1000(0.243)=243, \qquad
n_1(1-\hat{p})=1000(0.757)=757
    </md>
    <md>
n_2\hat{p}=1000(0.243)=243, \qquad
n_2(1-\hat{p})=1000(0.757)=757.
    </md> </p>
    <p>
      All four values are greater than <m>10</m>, so the normal approximation
      is appropriate.
    </p>
</solution>
<solution> <title> Statistical Test</title>
    <p> The test statistic is
        <md> z=\frac{(\hat{p}_1-\hat{p}_2)-0}
{\sqrt{\bar{p}(1-\bar{p})\left(\frac{1}{n_1}+\frac{1}{n_2}\right)}}
=\frac{0.21-0.276}
{\sqrt{(0.243)(0.757)\left(\frac{1}{1000}+\frac{1}{1000}\right)}}
=\frac{-0.066}{\sqrt{0.000367902}} \approx \frac{-0.066}{0.01918} \approx -3.44.
    </md></p>
</solution>
<solution> <title> p-value</title>
    <p> The p-value for a two-tailed test is <m> 2P(Z \lt -3.44)\approx 0.0006.  </m></p>
    <p>       Since the <term>p-value</term> is less than <m>0.025</m>, we reject
      <m>H_0</m>.     </p>
</solution>
<solution> <title> Conclusion</title>
    <p>
      At the <m>0.025</m> significance level, there is sufficient evidence to
      conclude that the population proportion of college students who report
      using marijuana today differs from the proportion from <m>10</m> years
      ago.
    </p>
  </solution>
</exercise>

<exercise> <title> Marijuana with TI-83 Plus </title>
<statement>
    <p>  A public health researcher wants to determine whether the proportion of
      college students who report using marijuana has changed over the past
      10 years. Ten years ago, a national survey found that <m>210</m>
      out of <m>1000</m> college students reported using marijuana. In a recent
      survey, <m>276</m> out of <m>1000</m> college students reported using
      marijuana.
    </p>
    <p>  At the <m>\alpha =0.025</m> significance level, test whether the population
      proportion of college students who use marijuana today differs from the
      proportion from ten years ago.
    </p>
<p> For the TI-83 Plus you need to enter the counts for each sample. The calculator will calculate the <m> \hat{p}</m> values for each sample, the pooled <m> \bar{p}</m> value, and the test statistic <m>z</m>. See the previous example for the formula setup. </p>
</statement>
 <solution><title> Hypotheses</title>
    <p>
      Let <m>p_1</m> represent the population proportion of college students who
      used marijuana ten years ago, and let <m>p_2</m> represent the
      population proportion of college students who use marijuana today.
    </p>
    <p>
      The hypotheses are
        <md> H_0:p_1 =p_2  \qquad H_a:p_1 \ne p_2     </md>
This is a two-tailed test. </p>
</solution>
<solution><title> Statistical Test with TI-83 Plus</title>
<p> Click on the <term>[STAT] </term> button and press the arrow twice to the right to highlight TESTS across the top and select option <term>6: 2-PropZtest</term> and press [ENTER] to select it. </p>
<figure xml:id="Marj2Proportion1">
            <caption>Selecting 2 Proportion Z Test on Calculator</caption>
            <image source="MarjProp1.png" width="90%">
                <shortdescription>Select option 6 then input values</shortdescription>
            </image>
        </figure> 
<p> Input the values from the samples. 
        <md>  x_1=210, \quad n_1=1000  </md>
    <md> x_2=276,  \quad n_2=1000 </md> </p>
<p> Identify the alternative hypothesis of <m> \ne p2</m> and then click on <term>Calculate</term> and press [ENTER] to evaluate the test. </p> 
<p> images </p>

<figure xml:id="Marj2Proportion2">
            <caption>Results 2 Proportion Z-Test Marijuana Usage</caption>
            <image source="MarjProp2.png" width="90%">
                <shortdescription>z-test value is -3.44 and p-value = 0.0006</shortdescription>
            </image>
        </figure>

<p> The display gives the alternative hypothesis of not equal, the test statistic is <m>z=-3.44</m> with <m> p-value = 0.0006</m>. Then it lists the sample proportions <m> p_1 = 0.21</m> and <m> p_2 = 0.276</m> and the pooled proportion <m> \bar{p} = 0.243 </m> </p> 
<p> If you select <term>Draw</term> it will graph the two-tailed test showing p-value = 0.0006. </p>
<p> Since the p-value is less than 0.025, reject the null hypothesis. </p>
<p> Sufficient evidence to conclude that the population proportion of college students who report using marijuana today differs from the proportion from ten years ago. </p> 

</solution> 
</exercise>

<p> Try the online TI-84 Applet <url href=" https://ti84calcpro.com/" /> </p>

<exercise xml:id="ex-two-proportion-audiology">
<title> Hearing Aids</title>
  <statement>
    <p>
      An audiologist wants to compare the proportion of patients who show
      measurable improvement in speech recognition after using two different
      hearing aid programs. A random sample of patients is assigned to
      Program A and Program B, and each patient is classified as either
      showing improvement or not showing improvement after six weeks.
    </p>
    <table>
      <title>Speech Recognition Improvement by Hearing Aid Program</title>
      <tabular>
        <row>
          <cell>Program</cell>
          <cell>Improved</cell>
          <cell>Not Improved</cell>
          <cell>Total</cell>
        </row>
        <row><cell>Program A</cell><cell>42</cell><cell>18</cell><cell>60</cell></row>
        <row><cell>Program B</cell><cell>31</cell><cell>29</cell><cell>60</cell></row>
      </tabular>
    </table>
    <p>
      At the <m>0.05</m> significance level, test whether the proportion of
      patients who improve is different for the two hearing aid programs.
    </p>
  </statement>
  <solution><title> Hypotheses</title>
    <p>
      This is a two-proportion <m>z</m>-test.
    </p>
    <p>
      Let <m>p_1</m> be the proportion of patients who improve with Program A,
      and let <m>p_2</m> be the proportion of patients who improve with
      Program B.
      The hypotheses are
      <md>H_0:p_1 = p_2</md>
      <md>H_a:p_1\ne p_2</md> for a two tailed test.
    </p>
  </solution>
  <solution> <title> Statistical Test</title>
    <p>
      The sample proportions are
      <md>
        \hat{p}_1=\frac{42}{60}=0.70
      </md>
       <md>
        \hat{p}_2=\frac{31}{60}\approx 0.5167.
      </md>
    </p>
    <p>
      Under the null hypothesis, the pooled proportion is
      <md>
        \hat{p}=\frac{42+31}{60+60}=\frac{73}{120}\approx 0.6083.
      </md>
    </p>
    <p>
      The test statistic is
      <md>
        z=
        \frac{\hat{p}_1-\hat{p}_2}
        {\sqrt{\hat{p}(1-\hat{p})\left(\frac{1}{n_1}+\frac{1}{n_2}\right)}}
        =   \frac{0.70-0.5167}
        {\sqrt{(0.6083)(0.3917)\left(\frac{1}{60}+\frac{1}{60}\right)}}
        \approx 2.05.
      </md>
    </p>
    <p>
      The <m>p</m>-value for a two-sided test is approximately <m>0.040</m>.
    </p>
  </solution>
  <solution> <title> Conclusion</title>

    <p>
      Since <m>p \lt0.05</m>, we reject <m>H_0</m>.
    </p>
    <p>
      There is sufficient evidence at the <m>0.05</m> significance level to
      conclude that the proportion of patients who improve differs between the
      two hearing aid programs.
    </p>
    <p>
      Because <m>\hat{p}_1 \gt  \hat{p}_2</m>, the data suggest that Program A
      has a higher improvement rate than Program B.
    </p>
  </solution>
</exercise>

<exercise xml:id="ex-two-proportion-postoperative">
<title> Postoperative Infection </title>
  <statement>
    <p>
      A nursing researcher wants to compare the proportion of patients who
      develop a postoperative infection under two different wound-care
      protocols. A random sample of surgical patients is assigned to Protocol A
      and Protocol B, and each patient is classified as either developing an
      infection or not developing an infection during recovery.
    </p>
    <table>
      <title>Postoperative Infection by Wound-Care Protocol</title>
      <tabular>
        <row>
          <cell>Protocol</cell>
          <cell>Infection</cell>
          <cell>No Infection</cell>
          <cell>Total</cell>
        </row>
        <row><cell>Protocol A</cell><cell>14</cell><cell>106</cell><cell>120</cell></row>
        <row><cell>Protocol B</cell><cell>27</cell><cell>93</cell><cell>120</cell></row>
      </tabular>
    </table>
    <p>
      At the <m>0.05</m> significance level, test whether the proportion of
      patients who develop a postoperative infection differs between the two
      wound-care protocols.
    </p>
  </statement>
  <solution><title> Hypotheses </title>
    <p>
      This is a two-proportion <m>z</m>-test.
    </p>
    <p>
      Let <m>p_1</m> be the proportion of patients who develop an infection
      under Protocol A, and let <m>p_2</m> be the proportion of patients who
      develop an infection under Protocol B. The hypotheses are
      <md>H_0:p_1=p_2</md>
      and
      <md>H_a:p_1\ne p_2</md>.
    </p>
  </solution>
  <solution> <title> Statistical Test</title>
    <p>
      The sample proportions are
      <md>
        \hat{p}_1=\frac{14}{120}\approx 0.1167
      </md>
      and
      <md>
        \hat{p}_2=\frac{27}{120}=0.225.
      </md>
    </p>
    <p>
      Under the null hypothesis, the pooled proportion is
      <md>
        \hat{p}=\frac{14+27}{120+120}=\frac{41}{240}\approx 0.1708.
      </md>
    </p>
    <p>
      The test statistic is
      <md>
        z=     \frac{\hat{p}_1-\hat{p}_2}
        {\sqrt{\hat{p}(1-\hat{p})\left(\frac{1}{n_1}+\frac{1}{n_2}\right)}}
        =     \frac{0.1167-0.225}
        {\sqrt{(0.1708)(0.8292)\left(\frac{1}{120}+\frac{1}{120}\right)}}
        \approx -2.22.
      </md>
    </p>
    <p>
      The <m>p</m>-value for a two-sided test is approximately <m>0.026</m>.
    </p>
  </solution>
  <solution> <title> Conclusion</title>
    <p>
      Since <m>p \lt 0.05</m>, we reject <m>H_0</m>.
    </p>
    <p>
      There is sufficient evidence at the <m>0.05</m> significance level to
      conclude that the proportion of patients who develop a postoperative
      infection differs between the two wound-care protocols.
    </p>
    <p>
      Because <m>\hat{p}_1 \lt \hat{p}_2</m>, the data suggest that Protocol A
      has a lower infection rate than Protocol B.
    </p>
  </solution>
</exercise>

<exercise xml:id="ex-two-proportion-groundwater">
<title>Groundwater</title>
  <statement>
    <p>
      Earth scientists want to compare the proportion of groundwater wells that
      test above the safe nitrate ion limit of 3.0 mg/L in two agricultural regions. A random  sample of wells is selected from Region A and Region B, and each well is classified as either above the safe nitrate limit or not above the safe nitrate limit.
    </p>
    <table>
      <title>Groundwater Wells Above Safe Nitrate Limit</title>
      <tabular>
        <row>
          <cell>Region</cell>
          <cell>Above Limit</cell>
          <cell>Not Above Limit</cell>
          <cell>Total</cell>
        </row>
        <row><cell>Region A</cell><cell>36</cell><cell>84</cell><cell>120</cell></row>
        <row><cell>Region B</cell><cell>22</cell><cell>98</cell><cell>120</cell></row>
      </tabular>
    </table>
    <p>
      At the <m>0.05</m> significance level, test whether the proportion of
      wells above the safe nitrate limit differs between the two regions.
    </p>
  </statement>
  <solution><title> Hypotheses</title> 
    <p>
      This is a two-proportion <m>z</m>-test.
    </p>
    <p>
      Let <m>p_1</m> be the proportion of wells above the safe nitrate limit in
      Region A, and let <m>p_2</m> be the proportion of wells above the safe
      nitrate limit in Region B. The hypotheses are
      <md>H_0:p_1=p_2</md>
       <md>H_a:p_1\ne p_2</md>.
    </p>
</solution>
  <solution> <title> Statistical Test</title>
    <p>
      The sample proportions are
      <md>\hat{p}_1=\frac{36}{120}=0.30</md>
       <md>\hat{p}_2=\frac{22}{120}\approx 0.1833</md>.
    </p>
    <p>
      Under the null hypothesis, the pooled proportion is
      <md>
        \hat{p}=\frac{36+22}{120+120}=\frac{58}{240}\approx 0.2417.
      </md>
    </p>
    <p>
      The test statistic is
      <m>
        z=   \frac{\hat{p}_1-\hat{p}_2}
        {\sqrt{\hat{p}(1-\hat{p})\left(\frac{1}{n_1}+\frac{1}{n_2}\right)}}
        =    \frac{0.30-0.1833}
        {\sqrt{(0.2417)(0.7583)\left(\frac{1}{120}+\frac{1}{120}\right)}}
        \approx 2.11.
      </m>
    </p>
    <p>
      The <m>p</m>-value for a two-sided test is approximately <m>0.035</m>.
    </p>
</solution>
  <solution> <title> Conclusion</title>
    <p>
      Since <m>p lt 0.05</m>, we reject <m>H_0</m>.
    </p>
    <p>
      There is sufficient evidence at the <m>0.05</m> significance level to
      conclude that the proportion of wells above the safe nitrate limit differs
      between the two regions.
    </p>
    <p>
      Because <m>\hat{p}_1 \gt  \hat{p}_2</m>, the data suggest that Region A
      has a higher proportion of wells above the safe nitrate ion limit of 3.0 mg/L than
      Region B.
    </p>
  </solution>
</exercise>

<exercise xml:id="ex-two-proportion-articulation-methods">
<title> Articulation Methods</title> 
  <statement>
    <p>
      A speech-language pathologist wants to compare the proportion of children
      who show improvement in articulation after receiving one of two different
      therapy approaches. A random sample of children receives Therapy A through <em>oral-motor exercise</em> to strength the mouth, lips and tongue for more precise sound production, and another random sample receives Therapy B by <em>sound modeling </em>where the  child imitates it during play-based drills. After eight weeks, each child is classified as either showing improvement in articulation or not showing improvement.
    </p>
    <table>
      <title>Articulation Improvement by Therapy Approach</title>
      <tabular>
        <row>
          <cell>Therapy Approach</cell>
          <cell>Improved</cell>
          <cell>Did Not Improve</cell>
          <cell>Total</cell>
        </row>
        <row><cell>Therapy A</cell><cell>34</cell><cell>16</cell><cell>50</cell></row>
        <row><cell>Therapy B</cell><cell>25</cell><cell>25</cell><cell>50</cell></row>
      </tabular>
    </table>
    <p>
      At the <m>0.05</m> significance level, test whether the proportion of
      children who improve differs between the two therapy approaches.
    </p>
  </statement>
  <solution><title> Hypotheses</title> 
    <p>
      This is a two-proportion <m>z</m>-test.
    </p>
    <p>
      Let <m>p_1</m> be the proportion of children who improve with Therapy A,
      and let <m>p_2</m> be the proportion of children who improve with
      Therapy B. The hypotheses are
      <md>H_0:p_1=p_2</md>
      and
      <md>H_a:p_1\ne p_2</md>.
    </p>
</solution>
  <solution> <title> Statistical Test</title>
    <p>  The sample proportions are
      <md>\hat{p}_1=\frac{34}{50}=0.68</md>
       <md>\hat{p}_2=\frac{25}{50}=0.50</md>.
    </p>
    <p>
      Under the null hypothesis, the pooled proportion is
      <md>     \hat{p}=\frac{34+25}{50+50}=\frac{59}{100}=0.59.
      </md>
    </p>
    <p>
      The test statistic is
      <md>
        z=     \frac{\hat{p}_1-\hat{p}_2}
        {\sqrt{\hat{p}(1-\hat{p})\left(\frac{1}{n_1}+\frac{1}{n_2}\right)}}
</md>
<md> z   =      \frac{0.68-0.50}
        {\sqrt{(0.59)(0.41)\left(\frac{1}{50}+\frac{1}{50}\right)}}
        \approx 1.84.
      </md>
    </p>
    <p>
      The <m>p</m>-value for a two-sided test is approximately <m>0.066</m>.
    </p>
</solution>
  <solution> <title> Conclusion</title>
    <p>
      Since <m>p \gt 0.05</m>, we fail to reject <m>H_0</m>.
    </p>
    <p>
      There is not sufficient evidence at the <m>0.05</m> significance level to
      conclude that the proportion of children who improve differs between the
      two therapy approaches.
    </p>
    <p>
      Although the sample proportion is higher for Therapy A, the difference is
      not statistically significant at the 0.05 level.
    </p>
  </solution>
</exercise>

<exercise xml:id="ex-two-proportion-sleep-psychology">
<title> Sleep Quality</title>
  <statement>
    <p>
      A psychologist wants to compare the proportion of participants who report
      improved sleep quality after using one of two different stress-reduction
      programs. A random sample of participants is assigned to Program A, journaling technique to write down anxious thoughts, and another random sample is assigned to Program B, a progressive muscle relaxation. After four weeks, each participant is classified as either reporting improved sleep quality or not reporting improvement.
    </p>
    <table>
      <title>Improved Sleep Quality by Stress-Reduction Program</title>
      <tabular>
        <row>
          <cell>Program</cell>
          <cell>Improved Sleep</cell>
          <cell>Did Not Improve</cell>
          <cell>Total</cell>
        </row>
        <row><cell>Program A</cell><cell>48</cell><cell>32</cell><cell>80</cell></row>
        <row><cell>Program B</cell><cell>36</cell><cell>44</cell><cell>80</cell></row>
      </tabular>
    </table>
    <p>
      At the <m>0.05</m> significance level, test whether the proportion of
      participants who report improved sleep quality differs between the two
      stress-reduction programs.
    </p>
  </statement>
  <solution><title> Hypotheses</title> 
    <p>
      This is a two-proportion <m>z</m>-test.
    </p>
    <p>
      Let <m>p_1</m> be the proportion of participants who report improved sleep
      quality in Program A, and let <m>p_2</m> be the proportion of participants
      who report improved sleep quality in Program B. The hypotheses are
      <md>H_0:p_1=p_2</md>
      and
      <md>H_a:p_1\ne p_2</md>.
    </p>
</solution>
  <solution> <title> Statistical Test</title>
    <p>
      The sample proportions are
      <md>\hat{p}_1=\frac{48}{80}=0.60</md>
       <md>\hat{p}_2=\frac{36}{80}=0.45</md>.
    </p>
    <p>
      Under the null hypothesis, the pooled proportion is
      <m>
        \hat{p}=\frac{48+36}{80+80}=\frac{84}{160}=0.525.
      </m>
    </p>
    <p>
      The test statistic is
      <md>
        z=    \frac{0.60-0.45}
        {\sqrt{(0.525)(0.475)\left(\frac{1}{80}+\frac{1}{80}\right)}}
        \approx 1.90.
      </md>
    </p>
    <p>
      The <m>p</m>-value for a two-sided test is approximately <m>0.057</m>.
    </p>
</solution>
  <solution> <title> Conclusion</title>
    <p>
      Since <m>p \gt 0.05</m>, we fail to reject <m>H_0</m>.
    </p>
    <p>
      There is not sufficient evidence at the 0.05 significance level to
      conclude that the proportion of participants who report improved sleep
      quality differs between the two stress-reduction programs.
    </p>
    <p>
      Although the sample proportion is higher for Program A, the difference is
      not statistically significant at the 0.05 level.
    </p>
  </solution>
</exercise>

<exercise xml:id="ex-two-proportion-renew">
<title> Renewals</title>
  <statement>
    <p>
      A company wants to compare the proportion of customers who renew their
      annual subscription after receiving one of two different email reminders.
      A random sample of customers receives Email A, and another random sample
      receives Email B. Each customer is then classified as either renewing the
      subscription or not renewing it.
    </p>
    <table>
      <title>Subscription Renewal by Email Reminder</title>
      <tabular>
        <row>
          <cell>Email Reminder</cell>
          <cell>Renewed</cell>
          <cell>Did Not Renew</cell>
          <cell>Total</cell>
        </row>
        <row><cell>Email A</cell><cell>78</cell><cell>102</cell><cell>180</cell></row>
        <row><cell>Email B</cell><cell>59</cell><cell>121</cell><cell>180</cell></row>
      </tabular>
    </table>
    <p>
      At the <m>0.05</m> significance level, test whether the proportion of
      customers who renew differs between the two email reminders.
    </p>
  </statement>
  <solution><title>Hypotheses</title> 
    <p>
      This is a two-proportion <m>z</m>-test.
    </p>
    <p>
      Let <m>p_1</m> be the proportion of customers who renew after receiving
      Email A, and let <m>p_2</m> be the proportion of customers who renew after
      receiving Email B. The hypotheses are
      <md>H_0:p_1=p_2</md>
      and
      <md>H_a:p_1\ne p_2</md>.
    </p>
</solution>
  <solution> <title> Statistical Test</title>
    <p>
      The sample proportions are
      <md>\hat{p}_1=\frac{78}{180}=0.4333</md>
      <md>\hat{p}_2=\frac{59}{180}=0.3278</md>.
    </p>
    <p>
      Under the null hypothesis, the pooled proportion is
      <md>
        \hat{p}=\frac{78+59}{180+180}=\frac{137}{360}\approx 0.3806.
      </md>
    </p>
    <p>
      The test statistic is
      <md>
        z=     \frac{\hat{p}_1-\hat{p}_2}
        {\sqrt{\hat{p}(1-\hat{p})\left(\frac{1}{n_1}+\frac{1}{n_2}\right)}}
        =     \frac{0.4333-0.3278}
        {\sqrt{(0.3806)(0.6194)\left(\frac{1}{180}+\frac{1}{180}\right)}}
        \approx 2.08.
      </md>
    </p>
    <p>
      The <m>p</m>-value for a two-sided test is approximately <m>0.038</m>.
    </p>
</solution>
  <solution> <title> Conclusion</title>
    <p>   Since <m>p \lt 0.05</m>, we reject <m>H_0</m>.    
   </p>
    <p>  There is sufficient evidence at the <m>0.05</m> significance level to
      conclude that the proportion of customers who renew differs between the
      two email reminders.
    </p>
    <p>
      Because <m>\hat{p}_1 \gt  \hat{p}_2</m>, the data suggest that Email A
      leads to a higher subscription renewal rate than Email B.
    </p>
  </solution>
</exercise>


  </subsection>

 


</section>
